vectorData.altText: 5. Identify the class of tissue. Be specific.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That’s right! Smooth muscle tissue can be identified by i) the absence of striations, ii) the one, elongated nucleus in each cell and iii) the tapering, “spindle-shape” of the cells.

Smooth muscle cells are the smallest muscle cells. They are non-striated, so their cytoplasm appears homogeneously pink. They are spindle shaped, so their nuclei appear elongated in longitudinal section (left). In cross section (right), their nuclei are seen to be centrally located, and because they taper, many cells appear to lack nuclei, having been cut toward their ends. Unlike other muscle tissue, the nuclei are large relative to the cells.
